Histogram

A Histogram is a graphical representation of the distribution of numerical (continuous) data. It divides the data into intervals called bins and shows how many values fall into each bin.

Unlike a bar chart, histogram bars touch each other because the data is continuous.

Definition

A histogram is a plot that displays the frequency distribution of a continuous variable using adjacent bars.

Example

Suppose students' marks are:

32, 35, 37, 41, 43, 45, 46, 52, 55, 58, 61, 64, 68, 72, 75

Marks (Bins)	Frequency
30–39	3
40–49	4
50–59	3
60–69	3
70–79	2

Histogram:

30-39  ███
40-49  ████
50-59  ███
60-69  ███
70-79  ██

When to Use Histogram

Use a histogram when:

Data is continuous
You want to understand the distribution
You want to detect:
Skewness
Outliers
Peaks (modes)
Spread of data
Histogram in Python
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.hist(df['Age'], bins=10)
plt.xlabel("Age")
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
plt.title("Age Distribution")
plt.show()
Meaning of bins

Bins divide the data into groups.

Example:

Age:
18 20 21 23 25 28 30 35 40

bins = 3

18–25
26–33
34–40

More bins → More detailed graph

Fewer bins → Simpler graph

